{
    "Description": "<h3>DEPRECATED – This function is no longer available and will throw an error if called.</h3><p><br></p><h3>Status</h3><p>This function was <strong>removed in Lua 5.1</strong> and is <strong>not available</strong> in current Lua versions (including the Lua version used by Iguana). Any attempt to call it will immediately result in an error.</p><p><br></p><h3>Reason for Deprecation</h3><p>Lua no longer allows explicitly setting the length of a table. Table length is now determined dynamically by the <strong>highest consecutive numeric index starting from 1</strong>. If there are gaps in the sequence, the <code>#</code> operator will only count up to the last contiguous numeric key.</p><p><br></p><h3>Migration Tip</h3><p>There is no replacement for <code>table.setn</code> because explicit length setting is no longer needed or supported. Just manipulate the table contents directly and allow Lua’s native behavior to determine the effective length.</p><h3><br></h3><h3>Notes</h3><ul><li>To avoid confusion with <code style=\"background-color: rgb(240, 240, 240);\">#table</code>, avoid inserting sparse numeric keys unless you're intentionally creating sparse data structures.</li><li>If a table needs to store arbitrary keys or sparse arrays, always access values directly by their key rather than relying on <code style=\"background-color: rgb(240, 240, 240);\">#</code>.</li></ul><p><br></p><h3>Behavior</h3><pre class=\"ql-syntax\" spellcheck=\"false\">local t = {\n&nbsp; &nbsp;[1] = \"iNTERFACEWARE\",\n&nbsp; &nbsp;[2] = \"IguanaX\",\n&nbsp; &nbsp;[5] = true\n}\ntrace(#t)&nbsp; -- Output: 2 (because 3 and 4 are missing)\n</pre>",
    "Name": "table.setn",
    "Parameters": null,
    "ParameterTable": false,
    "SummaryLine": "*DEPRECATED* - This function is no longer available and will throw an error if called."
}